Accepting contributions at the creative part even if they are not exactly what you

initially imagined, helps create a collective vision of the final product. This is invaluable as you will not always be online (except if your project is a full-time job) to check things out. Somebody else will be though, and it's very important that they can give some advice towards to the right direction
Give good guidelines. This not only will help your contributors keep in line with the overall goal but

* It will make it easy to discard things you don't like. Most of the time things you don't like are because they don't adhere to self imposed guidelines even if those are not articulated anywhere. If they are, the job is easier.

* Beware of too strict guidelines and overeager discarding of non-adhering proposals. There will come a time where you will want to break your own guidelines, you'll have to be able to do that without being too much of a dick.

* Providing a project X from which to shamelessly copycat from as a fallback is a good tactic. Using opensource or dead projects for this is best so that you avoid potential litigation. This way if a contributor doesn't know how to spec something he can go and check how project X did it and get some ideas. Make sure you clearly state things you hate about project X to make sure they don't end up in your project.
Don't stop thinking about your grand vision, and work in a way that enables switching to that without re-doing everything from scratch
Deep down you know what compromises make set a divine creation apart from a human well made product and which downright destroy your project.
Accept the first if you see significant community gains, defend the latter with every possible weapon. Leave/fork the project if you fail.
Yeah, it'd be cool to create a history making product from version one, but what if this means there's no product to ship because everybody except the lead designer abandoned ship?
Having a successful, coherent product that works and is not ugly is the best way to make version 2.0 awesome. You also get to fix a couple of things that went wrong, and provide an exciting new look.
Company-led open source projects, and source-over-wall projects are obviously not included. These kind of projects have a traditional approach to design.
Most pure-community projects are starving for contributors. UI is a magnet for new contributors:
- It's user facing
- Looks easy (Spoiler: it isn't)
- Everybody wants to make his usecase easy
It's too easy to scare away these people that come over to help if you just discard their ideas.
So what is the best approach?
